## 3️⃣ Power Budget Summary

| Load | Source | Est. Current | Pin / Rail |
|---|---|---|---|
| Servo (idle) | External 5V | ~150 mA | External rail |
| Servo (moving) | External 5V | ~300–500 mA | External rail |
| Servo (stall) | External 5V | ~500–650 mA | External rail |
| LED Red (on) | D5 | **~14 mA** | (5V−2V)/220Ω |
| LED Yellow (on) | D6 | **~14 mA** | (5V−2V)/220Ω |
| LED Green (on) | D7 | **~14 mA** | (5V−2V)/220Ω |
| Button pull-up | Internal | ~0.1 mA | Negligible |
| **Arduino 5V rail** | USB/Barrel | **≤ 42 mA** | ✅ Safe (limit 200 mA) |
| **Per signal pin max** | Arduino | **14 mA** | ✅ Safe (limit 20 mA) |
| **External rail** | Ext. 5V | up to 650 mA | ✅ Isolated from Arduino |

> ✅ **Result:** Arduino rail only powers the LEDs + logic (~42 mA peak). Servo is fully offloaded to external supply. No pin exceeds the 20 mA per-pin limit.

---

## 4️⃣ "What Can Go Wrong" Checklist for Beginners

### 🔴 Critical Mistakes
| # | Mistake | Consequence | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Powering servo from Arduino 5V pin** | Arduino regulator overheats, resets, or burns out (servo needs up to 650 mA) | Use external 5V supply for servo VCC |
| 2 | **Forgetting common ground** | Servo won't respond; erratic signal behavior; possible damage | Wire external supply GND → Arduino GND |
| 3 | **No resistor on LEDs** | LED burns out instantly; signal pin may be damaged | Always use 220Ω–330Ω in series |

### 🟡 Common Errors
| # | Mistake | Consequence | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| 4 | **Using `delay()` instead of `millis()`** | Button becomes unresponsive during sweep | Non-blocking timing with `millis()` (already done) |
| 5 | **Skipping button debounce** | One press registers as 5–10 toggles | Debounce with 50 ms window (already done) |
| 6 | **Attaching servo before `setup()` runs** | Servo may jitter or jump to random position | `attach()` inside `setup()`, write 0° first |
| 7 | **Two loads sharing one signal pin** | Pin draws >20 mA → damaged pin or MCU | One component per signal pin — always |

### 🟢 Good Practice Reminders
| # | Tip |
|---|---|
| 8 | Use a **capacitor (100–470 µF) across external 5V rail** to absorb servo current spikes |
| 9 | Check your **USB cable** can supply enough current if powering Arduino via USB (~500 mA limit) |
| 10 | Servo signal wire is only valid while Arduino is powered — **power Arduino before external supply** |
| 11 | When in doubt, use a **multimeter** to measure actual current before connecting to Arduino pins |

